# React 19 Patterns

Prefer React 19 APIs over older alternatives.

## `use()` for promises and context

Use `use()` to unwrap promises (e.g. Next.js async params) or read context inside conditionals. It replaces `useContext` and manual `.then()` chains.

```tsx
import { use } from "react";

export default function Page({ params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }) {
  const { id } = use(params);
  return <Detail id={id} />;
}
```

## `useActionState` for form mutations

Pair with `<form action={...}>` for server-round-trip forms. Returns `[state, formAction, isPending]`.

```tsx
const [state, submitAction, isPending] = useActionState(createLayer, initialState);

return (
  <form action={submitAction}>
    <input name="name" />
    <button disabled={isPending}>Save</button>
    {state.error && <p>{state.error}</p>}
  </form>
);
```

## `useTransition` for non-urgent updates

Wrap expensive state updates so they don't block typing or animations.

```tsx
const [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition();

function handleFilter(query: string) {
  setInputValue(query);
  startTransition(() => {
    setFilteredResults(filterLayers(query));
  });
}
```

## `useOptimistic` for instant feedback

Show the expected result immediately while the async operation runs.

```tsx
const [optimisticLayers, addOptimistic] = useOptimistic(layers);

async function handleAdd(layer: Layer) {
  addOptimistic([...optimisticLayers, layer]);
  await apiFetch("/api/layers", { method: "POST", body: layer });
}
```

## Ref cleanup functions

Return a cleanup function from ref callbacks instead of using `useEffect` for DOM setup/teardown.

```tsx
<canvas ref={(node) => {
  if (!node) return;
  const ctx = node.getContext("2d");
  return () => { /* cleanup */ };
}} />
```
